article.description:
Ben Wallace followed up his busy All-Star weekend
with 22 rebounds, and Chauncey Billups scored 20 points as the
Detroit Pistons beat the Chicago Bulls 89-79 Tuesday night their
fifth straight victory.
article.headline: Wallace hauls down 22 boards in Pistons' win
article.linkText: Pistons continue dominance of Bulls in Chicago
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- No one would have questioned Ben Wallace if he'd taken the night off or had a quiet game.
Wallace

After all, the last 10 days been a drain, both mentally and physically. He missed the Detroit Pistons' last game before the break because of his mother's death, then played in the All-Star game Sunday night after attending her funeral in Alabama the day before. But Wallace is all about hard work, and he proved that again Tuesday night as he grabbed 22 rebounds and blocked two shots to lead the Pistons to an 89-79 victory over the Chicago Bulls. "He's a worker,'' said Clifford Robinson, who finished with 10 points, one of five Pistons to score in double figures. "The fact that he has been off (1{) games, it didn't show. He's going to go out and give you what he's got every night.'' Wallace set the tone for the Pistons, who won their fifth straight. Though they shot just 34 percent, they held their fifth straight opponent below 90 and outrebounded the Bulls 55-44 -- including a whopping 23-10 advantage on the offensive boards. The Pistons have now beaten the Bulls in 16 of their last 18 meetings, and are 6-0 at the United Center since January 2000. "I didn't want to let my personal life get involved in my job,'' said Wallace, who finished two shy of his season high in rebounds. "I put stuff from this weekend behind me and I wanted to go back to work.'' The Bulls might want to take note of his attitude. Chicago turned the ball over on four of its first six possessions and fell behind early. Jalen Rose scored 18 of his 27 points in the third quarter, but the Bulls could never recover after falling behind early. It was the their first loss at home since Jan. 2, snapping a five-game winning streak, and fans booed them as the clock ran out. "We got outworked,'' Rose said. "It seemed like every offensive rebound fell their way. What really hurt us was the multiple tries. You are not going to win when only three players have what we call a good game.'' Especially when only two of those players were starters. Donyell Marshall had 12 rebounds and 12 points despite playing much of the second half with a sprained ankle. But Eddie Robinson, Eddy Curry and Jay Williams -- inserted into the starting lineup Tuesday night -- combined for only 18 points and eight rebounds. "You shouldn't look at it as looking over your shoulder,'' coach Bill Cartwright said. "You should look at it as seize the moment.'' After trailing from midway through the first quarter, the Bulls pulled within 28-25 on Jamal Crawford's 20-footer with 6:37 to play in the first half. But Clifford Robinson hit a 3-pointer to spark a 17-6 run that put Detroit ahead 45-31. And for a team with as nasty a defense as Detroit's, that's tantamount to having a 30-point lead. "We thought it was important after the break, coming in here and getting off to a good start,'' Wallace said. "We had to start by cleaning up the boards. Coming off the break, there's going to be a lot of missed shots. You can't afford to let teams get second shots. They'll get their energy that way.'' The Bulls did manage to chip away at the lead as Rose, limited by foul trouble in the first half, had 18 points in the third quarter. They got within six several times, only to have the Pistons answer right back. One time it was Corliss Williamson, scoring on a running jumper. Another time it was Mehmet Okur, drilling a 3-pointer. Still another was Richard Hamilton with a 3 of his own. Rose made a pull-up jumper with less than two seconds left to cut Detroit's lead to 73-66 heading into the final period. But Williamson opened the fourth with a jumper, the Bulls shot airballs on two straight possessions, and Jon Barry made a 3-pointer as Detroit took a commanding 78-66 lead. "It was very important,'' Wallace said. "Some teams slack off a little bit after the break, some teams pick up. We want to be one of those teams.'' Game notes
Bulls F Marcus Fizer will have surgery Friday to repair a torn right ACL. Rehabilitation is expected to last six-to-eight months. ... Bulls C Tyson Chandler was out of the starting lineup, punishment for missing the team's practice Monday. Chandler, who played in Rookie-Sophomore Challenge on All-Star Saturday, got to the Atlanta airport two hours early, but got stuck in an unbelievably lengthy check-in line and missed his flight. "I missed practice, I can't be mad about it,'' Chandler said.
